revision.text:
'''Elpidius''' or '''Elpidios''' ({{lang-el|{{lang|grc|Ἐλπίδιος}}}}) was a [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] aristocrat and governor of [[Sicily (theme)|Sicily]], who was accused of conspiring against Empress [[Irene of Athens]] (r. 780–802). This forced him to rebel, and after being defeated he defected to the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] and was recognized there as [[Byzantine emperor]].

==Biography==
[[File:Seal of Elpidius (Schlumberger).png|thumb|right|250px|Seal of Elpidius]]
Nothing is known of Elpidius before February 781, when Empress Irene (r. 780–802) appointed him as governor (''[[strategos]]'') of the [[Theme (Byzantine district)|theme]] of [[Sicily (theme)|Sicily]]. At the time, he already held the highest Byzantine dignity, that of ''[[patrikios]]'', and the chronicler [[Theophanes the Confessor]] simply mentions that he had held the governorship of Sicily in the past, either under [[Leo IV the Khazar]] (r. 775–780) or possibly [[Constantine V]] (r. 741–775).<ref name="PmbZ">{{harvnb|Winkelmann|Lilie|Ludwig|Pratsch|1999|pp=486–487}}.</ref><ref name="Treadgold66">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1991|p=66}}.</ref> Soon after, however, on 15 April, Irene was informed that he had supported a plot, discovered in October of the previous year to depose her and elevate the ''[[Caesar (title)|Caesar]]'' [[Nikephoros (Caesar)|Nikephoros]], the eldest surviving son of Constantine V, to power. Irene immediately dispatched the ''[[spatharios]]'' Theophilos to Sicily to bring Elpidius back to [[Constantinople]]. Although his wife and children were left behind in Constantinople, Elpidius refused the summons and was supported by the people and the local army. It does not seem that Elpidius declared himself explicitly in revolt against Irene, but the Empress nevertheless had his wife and children publicly whipped and imprisoned in the capital's ''[[praetorium]]''.<ref name="PmbZ"/><ref name="Treadgold66"/> 

In autumn of 781 or early 782, Irene dispatched against him a large fleet under a trusted court eunuch, the ''patrikios'' Theodore. Elpidius's own military forces were meager, and after several battles he was defeated. Along with his lieutenant, the ''[[dux]]'' Nikephoros (probably the commander of [[Calabria]]), he gathered what remained of the theme's treasury and fled to [[North Africa]], where the Arab authorities welcomed him. There, he had himself proclaimed emperor, a claim that was formally—but apparently not very seriously—acknowledged by the Abbasid government.<ref name="PmbZ"/><ref name="Treadgold67">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1991|p=67}}.</ref> His life thereafter is obscure, except for his participation in a large-scale campaign (reportedly 40,000 men) against Byzantium in 792 or 794. The Abbasids probably hoped that they could set him up as a rival emperor in at least part of [[Asia Minor]], but the invading army was met with the onset of an early and heavy [[winter]], losing many men to [[cold]], and was forced to retreat.<ref name="PmbZ"/><ref name="Treadgold103">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1991|p=103}}.</ref> According to [[Syriac language|Syriac]] sources, he was still alive in 802, when Irene was deposed by [[Nikephoros I]] (r. 802–811). When learning of this event, he is said to have advised [[Abd al-Malik ibn Salih]], Emir of [[Upper Mesopotamia|Mesopotamia]], to "throw away his silk and put on his armour", as Nikephoros would pursue a more aggressive policy against the Abbasids than Irene.<ref name="Treadgold127">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1991|p=127}}.</ref>

